ved tremendously bad press. Today it is mostly regarded as an outdated historical concept. Theories that have evolved since the abandonment of verificationism can, however, help overcome some of its key problems. More specifically, an adequate criterion of significance can be derived from a combination of modern theories of justification and belief revision, along with a formal semantics for counterfactuals. In view of these potential improvements, the abandonment of verificationism appears premature. Half a century following its decline, it might be about time to revisit this disreputable view. The author argues in favor of a weak form of verificationism. This approach could be referred to as minimal verificationism, as it involves a weakening of traditional verificationist principles in various respects while maintaining their core idea.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLogical positivism. 0aVerification (Empiricism). 4aLogischer Empirismus. 4aSignifikanzkriterium. 4aVerifizierbarkeit. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aCriterion of Significance.  aLogical Empiricism.  aVerificationism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2015z9783110438680oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97815015020020 cprintz978150151057140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150150198240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501501982423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501501982/original  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-076251-8  DG 